Dalrymple, Hilda Wanita*, nee Highman
Source--The Journal Leader   Caldwell, Ohio
Published--Monday    July 14, 1997
            Wanita ======= style='mso-spacerun:yes'> Caldwell, Ohio
Published--Monday July 14, 1997
Wanita >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Dalrymple, 71, of Woodsfield, died Sunday, July 6, 1997 at her home.
She was born November 8, 1925 in Monroe County, daughter of the late Charles Franklin and Pearl Josephine Nalley Highman.
Mrs. Dalrymple was preceded in death by her husband, Albert Dalrymple, in 1996; a son, William Robert Dalrymple; four brothers, a sister, and two grandchildren.
She leaves five sons, Roger, Larry and Harry Dalrymple, all of Woodsfield, Herbert Dalrymple of Lewisville and Raymond Dalrymple of Akron; three daughters, Janice Matthews of Dexter City and Donna Clark and Cheryl Schwaben, both of Woodsfield; a sister Audrey Gatten Shafer of Lewisville; 24 grandchildren and six great-grandchildren.
Friends were received Tuesday from 4 to 9 p.m. at Bauer-Turner Funeral Home, Woodsfield, where services were held at 1 p.m. Wednesday with Fred Ricer officiating.
Burial was in Oaklawn Cemetery, Woodsfield.

Danford, Charles R
Jeffersonian Monday 20 October 1924
Charles R Danford, age 12 years, son of Mr. and Mrs. Garfield Danford of near Batesvile, died Sunday evening at 5:30 o'clock at the Cambridge hospital. The body was removed to the Stevens morgue and prepared for burial and Monday was taken to the late home. One week ago the boy was stricken with appendicitis and Tuesday was removed to the hospital where he underwent a surgical treatment. Peritonitis had developed and resulted.

The Marietta Times
Marietta, Ohio, Wednesday, November 13, 2002
Joyce Marlene Davis, Willey
CALDWELL - Joyce Marlene Davis, 59, of Slaters Road died Monday afternoon (Nov. 11, 2002) at Summit Acres Nursing Home in Caldwell after a short illness.
She was born Feb. 13, 1943, in Caldwell to Clinton Wayne and Sarah Mae Nichelson Willey. She was a 1961 graduate of Caldwell High School and had worked for 23 years as business manager for General Motors dealerships, including Cowgill Chevrolet, Bob's of Barnesville and finally Whitesides. She was currently employed as the director of the Joyce M. Davis Senior Citizens Center in Caldwell. She was active and widely known in business, professional and civic organizations.
She was a member and past worthy matron of Amazon Chapter 30, Order of Eastern Star; past president of the Noble County Chamber of Commerce; past president of the Noble County Business & Professional Women's Organization; member of the Ohio Business & Professional Women, in which she had held regional and state offices; founding member of Leadership Noble; member of the Citizens Advisory Board at the Noble Correctional Institute; and was a board member of the Ohio Hills Chapter of the American Red Cross. She was active in the United Way and had attended Keith United Methodist Church in Keithtown.
She is survived by her husband, Virgil "Butch" Davis, whom she married on April 16, 1966; five sisters, Joy Cunningham of Bradenton, Fla., Jewell (Riley) Dovenbarger of Mansfield, JoAnn (Richard) Stobbs of Westerville, June Hayes of Caldwell and Jeanne (Fred) Eschbaugh of Cambridge; three brothers, Don Willey of Mansfield, David (Etta) Willey of Sharon and Darwin Willey of Senecaville; and numerous nieces, nephews, grandnieces, grandnephews and cousins.
Services are at 1 p.m. Friday at McVay-Perkins Funeral Home in Caldwell with the Revs. William Pickenpaugh and Ken and Susan Hyland officiating. Burial will be in Olive Cemetery.
Friends may call from 7 to 9 p.m. today and 2 to 9 p.m. Thursday at the funeral home. The family will be present from 2 to 4 and 7 to 9 p.m. Thursday at the funeral home. The Noble County Business and Professional Women's Organization will conduct services at 7:30 p.m. today. Amazon Chapter 30, Order of Eastern Star, will conduct services at 7:30 p.m. Thursday.
Memorial contributions may be made to The Joy M. Davis Senior Citizens Center Memorial Fund. Envelopes will be provided at the funeral home. An online register book may be signed at www.mcvay-perkins.com.

Day, William E.
Source--On Line Obituaries
Day, William E.: The Angel of Death has again been hovering around us and has taken from our midst William E. Day. He was born at Rock Hill, Belmont Co., and died near Stafford, Monroe County Ohio, July 24, 1899, aged 60 yrs. 8 mo. 9 days. He enlisted in Co. G. and fought for his country as a loyal and brave man. He was married to Miss Margaret Dollman of near Leabnon, their lives being one of peace and happiness. Ten children were born unto them five boys and five girls, and his bereaved wife still survive him. He was converted and united to the M.E. church in 1870. The Methodist Ministry always found a hearty welcome in his home which was a true Christian home. His ten children being faithful members of the M.E. church. He was a gentleman widely known and highly respected by all who knew him. He was closely attached to his family and was a great sufferer from cancers during the three months of his sickness and as a true Christian he bore his suffering well. He was also a member of the John Archibald post, No 362 of Stafford. His comrades will miss him from their ranks as they have lost a good comrade who never will gather with the boys to be tribute to the loyal dead. He was a good kind father and loving husband and will be missed by the family circle when they gather around the family altar of which he was the guide and light as well as being missed by his many friends. Short devotional services was held at the house, July the 25th, 1899 followed by regular services by Revs. Smith and Martin a large concourse of relatives and friends followed him to his last resting place with his beloved comrades acting as pall bearers his remains were interred in the Stafford cemetery.

50th Wedding Anniversary
De Long, Guy and Mona
Source--Barnesville Enterprise     Barnesville, ======= style='mso-spacerun:yes'> Barnesville, >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Ohio

De Long, Guy and Mona, will celebrate their 50th wedding anniversary on June 5, 2004.
On June 5, 1954, Mona Stephen, daughter of the late Alex and Elma Stephen and Guy De Long, son of the late Joseph and Josephine De Long were united in marriage at the home of the Reverend J.V.A. Traylor of Woodsfield.
John and Delores Stephen attended the couple.
The couple were both employees at the former Cambridge M.H. and M.R. Center. Mr. De Long retired after serving 32 years, and 11 years at Byesville IGA.
Mrs. De Long retired following 36 years of service.
The couple are members od Salesville United Methodist Church.
The couple has six children; David (Debra)of Senecaville, Douglas (Rhonda) of Cambridge, Darryl (Sandra) of Salesville, Darren (Kerry) of Cambridge and Dennis and Dayle of Salesville.
Completing the family circle are nine grandchildren; Kevin, Dawn, Nicole, Dustin, Dominique, Karley, Taylor, Paige and Denise, and three great-grandchildren, Haley, Chloe and Emma.
The couple celebrated the special occasion during a dinner with their family in Amish Country.

Source--Spirit of Democracy    Woodsfield, ======= style='mso-spacerun:yes'> Woodsfield, >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Ohio
Published--April 16, 1982
 
======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711
DeVoe, Harry Augustus was born September 2, 1902 in Lewisville, Ohio, and departed this life Wednesday, April 7, 1982, in the Barnesville Hospital. <<<<<<< HEAD His parents were Frank S. and  Bertha Ann ======= His parents were Frank S. and Bertha Ann >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Gibson DeVoe.
He became a member of the Lewisville Methodist Church early in his life and was a faithful member for well over 50 years. For 26 years he served the church as its secretary and treasurer.
He was an active and helpful member of the Monroe County community. In his early adult years he taught school in Summit Township and managed a grocery store store in Woodsfield. Later, as a tax consultant and accountant, he was well known and respected throughout Monroe and Belmont Counties.
Failing health limited his activities during the past five years. However, at the time of his death, he was a member of the Stafford Masonic Lodge, Cambridge Knights Templer, and the Columbus Shrine. This year marked his completion of fifty years' membership in the Stafford Masonic Lodge.
A brother, Robert D. DeVoe, and a sister, Lucille O. Flauhaus, preceded him in death.
Surviving are his wife, Olga Scarborough DeVoe; one son, Robert F. DeVoe, of Greenfield, Indiana; one granddaughter, Dianne, and one grandson, Dana, also from Indiana. A brother, Virgil James DeVoe, and a sister, Lela Polen, of Lewisville, Ohio, also survive.
Masonic services were held April 9, 1982, at the Bauer and Turner Funeral Home. Funeral services were held April 10, 1982, at Lewisville Methodist Church, with Reverend James Gibbons and Reverend Lester Lehman officiating.
The family wishes to express their sincere appreciation to those who helped in any way to alleviate the sorrow, for floral tributes, memorial tributes, cards, letters, calls, food and the many other acts of kindness. We shall always be deeply grateful
 
Devoe, J. C.

Devore, Clair and James Ullman
Two Boys Drown Sunday Near Stafford
Died, June 8, 1944
Clair Devore Loses Life In Attempt To Rescue James Ullman:
Provided by Lena Kahrig Pettit, typed by Betty Lendon Matson
     A double ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> A double >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 drowning shocked the Stafford-Lewisville communities Sunday afternoon when two fine young men lost their lives in Clearfork Creek, about two miles southeast of Stafford. They were James Henry Ullman, who would have been 22 years of age on June 29 and Clair Devore who was 17 years old last November 6. Devore, a fairly good swimmer was in the water, which in places was 12 to 15 feet deep. He cautioned his friend not to come out too far and Ullman replied that he would wade close to the bank. As he was wading he suddenly disappeared, apparently stepping into a deep hole. Devore went to aid him and both were drowned.
     This is ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> This is >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 according to three ten year old boys, Donald and Charles Hines and Junior Robbins who were sitting on the bank. They summoned help and Leonard Hines and William Hawkins arrived almost immediately and Ullman was taken out of the water in about 15 minutes, but he couldn't be saved while Devore was in the water about 45 minutes.
     Devore was ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Devore was >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 graduated this year from the Lewisville High School and had done excellent work. He had won a four-year scholarship in college of agriculture at Ohio State University. He is survived by his parents, Mr. and Mrs. Delbert Devore of near Lewisville; one brother Carl who is with the armed forces in England and Glen of the home and four sisters, Mrs. Chester Deeker, Geraldine, Eileen and Joan of the home.
     Ullman is ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Ullman is >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 survived by his father, Walter Ullman and one sister. Mrs. Dorothy Kestner of Port Clinton. His only brother, Lester who preceded him in Africa last September. James had passed his pre-induction examination and was waiting to be called for service. He was graduated from the Lewisville High School.

Devore, Glenn E.
Glenn E. Devore, aged 20, son of Mr. and Mrs. R.L. Devore, 308 North Fifth street, passed away at the Swan hospital Thursday afternoon at 2:45 o'clock following an operation for appendicitis performed late Wednesday night.
The young man became ill Monday and his condition became critical Wednesday before he was removed to the hospital. General peritonitis had resulted before the operation was performed.
He was a popular young man and had a large number of friends. He had graduated from Cambridge High School, class of 1927, and in 1928 was graduated from Cambridge Business College. For the past two and one half years he had been employed as a clerk in the offices of the AT&T Co., in Cambridge. Mr. Devore united with the First M.E. church when he was 10 years of age. He was active in affairs of the church and took great interest in young people's work. His death is sincerely regretted by a wide circle of admirers.
In addition to his parents, he is survived by three sisters, Wilma, Vera, and Hila Mae, all of the home; one brother, Harold S., Zandesville, and grandparents, Mr. and Mrs. A.W. Lucas of Graysville and Mrs. William Sunnafrank, of Kimbolton. One brother is deceased.
He was an accomplished cornetist and played in the M.E. Sunday school orchestra, also in the high school orchestra when a student.
Funeral services will be held at the home Saturday afternoon at 1:30 o'clock, conducted by Rev. Ora Shoop, pastor of the First M.E. church. Burial will be made at Northwood cemetery.
 
Devore, Grace A.
Devore, Grace A. : Grace A. Devore, 84, of Granville, formerly of Zanesville, died Friday, July 22, 1988 in Licking Memorial Hospital, Newark. Mrs. Devore retired in 1968 as an elementary school teacher in Zanesville City Schools, and was a member of the National Retired Teachers Association and Ohio Retired Teacher Association. She was also a member of Muskingum Lodge 485 Order of Eastern Star, Zanesville. Mrs. Devore was a member of Sentenary United Methodist Church, Granville, where she was active in the United Methodist Women organization. She was born, October 12, 1903 in Summerfield, daughter of the late Edgar R. and Lillian Craig Harris. Her first husband, Lawrence Yoho, died in 1962 and her second husband, John H. Devore, died in 1978. She is survived by two step-daughters, Jacqueline Quinn and Karen Davis, both of Junction City, Kansas, two grandchildren, and several nieces and nephews. Friends called Sunday at McPeek Funeral Home in Granville, where Eastern Star services were held Sunday. Funeral services were held Monday at Sentenary United Methodist Church in Granville with the Rev. Duane E. Johnson officiating. Graveside services were held in Memorial Park Zanesville.
provided by Betty Lendon Matson

Robert Edwin Devore
          Robert Edwin Devore, 77, died Aug. 28, 2002.  He was a native of Graysville and was a resident of Jacksonville, Fla., for 43 years.
          He served in the U.S. Army during WW II with Company E 180th Infantry Regiment 45th Division Co.  He was employed by F.E. Myers Co. for 41 years, having managed the Jacksonville warehouse.
          Surviving are his loving wife of 56 years, Virginia Luburgh Devore; son, Steve Devore (Candy); three daughters, Mrs. Rob (Carol) Cox, Mrs. Conrad (Pam) Edwards, Mrs. Paul (Jill) Horwath; five grandchildren; Patrick and Michael Cox, Nathan and Chelsea Edward, Paul Horwath Jr.; four great grandchildren, Ethan and Andrew Cox, and April and Harley Horwath; sister Mrs. Larry (Ruth) Mackey; several nieces and nephews.
          He was preceded in death by his parents, George N. and Phyllis A. Devore; brother, George N. Devore, Jr.
          Friends are received Aug. 30 at Hardage-Gliddens Funeral Home, Jacksonville, Fla., where funeral services were held Aug. 31.
          Memorial contributions may be made to Disabled American Veterans, P.O. Box 16444, Jacksonville, Fla. 32245.

Diehl, Frank W.
The Spirit of Democracy Issue: Woodsfield, Ohio, June 9, 1932
Frank W. Diehl, aged 73, well known retired Woodsfield business man died at the home of his son, Donald Diehl on North Paul Street, last Saturday evening, June 4, 1932, at 9:00 after a protracted illness.
Funeral services were held Tuesday afternoon at 4:00 and were in charge of the Reverend W. H. Petry of the Woodsfield Presbyterian Church of which Church decedent was a member, assisted by the Reverend W. Jones of the Woodsfield Methodist Episcopal Church.
Mr. Diehl was a son of Mr. and Mrs. Peter Diehl pioneer residents of Woodsfield of Woodsfield, and after the of his father took over the management of the general store on South main street, the firm name being F. W. Diehl & Son. Mr. Diehl in the conduct of his business became widely acquainted and news of his will be received with sincere regret by scores of friends.
 Two sons, ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Two sons, >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Robert Diehl of Cambridge and Donald Diehl of Woodsfield survive. His wife, who before her marriage was Miss Anna Pope died 19 years ago. Two sisters also survive: Mrs. Hattie Miller of Cleveland and Mrs. Marie Okey of Sioux City, Iowa.
As a youth Mr. Diehl attended local schools and Bethany College, being a member of the Phi Si fraternity of that college. He was a great lover of music and spent years in its study and teaching.

Diehl, William
WILLIAM DIEHL----and Catherine Newhart were married in this County. He was born in Germany, October 17, 1832, while she was born in this County, September 21, 1838; her parents, Lenard and Salome (Sulsberger) Newhart, were among the early settlers of Summit township, enduring hardships incident to the settlement of a new country; her mother died July 7, 1881. William's parents, Henry and Elizabeth (Walter) Diehl, came from Germany in 1843, and settled in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, where they resided four years; from there they came to Wayne township, this County, which was at that time very thinly populated; from there they removed to the present residence of William, on section 11, Centre township. The children of Mr. and Mrs Diehl are: Henry C., born June 9, 1856, resides in Centre township; John William, November. 30, 1857, resides in Wayne township; George C., March 29, 1859, resides at home; Sophia S. (Bertram), August 15, 1860, resides in Centre township; Henrietta M., September 21, 1862, resides at home; Laura L., March 8, 1865, died January 5, 1875; Frederick M., May 22, 1867, resides at home; Anna M., June 13, 1870, died January 4, 1874; Louis L., November 3, 1872, died January 18, 1875; Louise C., Aug 18, 1875; resides at home; Forest E., March 27, 1878; Jacob A., born November 12, 1881. A brother of Mr. Diehl, John Conrad, was in the war of 1861, a member ofthe 77th Ohio Volunteer Infantry; served nine months and was honorably discharged. Mr. Diehl is a farmer and stock raiser. Address, Woodsfield, Monroe County, Ohio.

 Dietrich, ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Dietrich, >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 William E. Dietrich
William E. Dietrich Dies At Hannibal
Died, January 19, 1945
Provided by Lena Kahrig Pettit, typed by Betty Lendon Matson
     Saturday ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Saturday >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 afternoon, Monroe County, lost one of her best known citizens in the person of William F. Dietrich, whose occurred at his home near Hannibal at 4 o'clock. He retired Friday evening apparently as usual but became ill in the night, having suffered a cerebral hemorrhage. A physician was summoned but the strong physique that had served an active mind for nearly 79 years had yielded to the inevitable.
     Mr. ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Mr. >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Dietrich was born April 28, 1866, being one of a family of twelve children born to the late John and Sarah Dietrich, who moved from a farm near Welcome, W.Va. to the present farm on "BuckHill Bottom" when Mr. Dietrich was six years old. Here he spent his boyhood, received the customary rural school education and on February 27, 1890, he was united in marriage to Miss Sarah J. Cline. To this same home he brought his bride and here they reared their family, made a good living and a little more, supported schools and churches, and in short exemplified The American way of life at its best.
     Both ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Both >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 parents lived to realize the glory of age, that of seeing their children out in the world making good, and took a just pride therein.
     Recognized ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Recognized >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 by reason of character, ability and personality, Mr. Dietrich served his community in various capacities. Not only was he a faithful member of The Methodist Church at Hannibal, but he served on the church board for many years, also as member of the township school board and as township trustee, he was instrumental in securing
better school facilities and road improvement in his community. From 1912 to 1916 he served as County commissioner and at the time of his was a member of the County board of education, and had been for nine years. In both larger spheres he was an advocate of improvement and progress.
     Mr. and ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Mr. and >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Mrs. Dietrich took life in its stride, including the solicitude of those in military service of two wars. His son, Donald C. Dietrich, now treasurer and general manager of The Wheeling Wholesale Grocery Co. and member of Wheeling city council was a member of the first contingent of nine men to go to Camp Sherman in World War 1. They left for Camp Sherman on September 7, 1917.
     Funeral ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Funeral >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 services were held Tuesday afternoon at The Rush Funeral Home in Clarington in charge of his pastor, Rev. Kenneth Evans, and were largely attended. Sympathy and esteem of friends were evidenced by many floral offerings from individuals and organizations.
     Interment was made in the family lot in The BuckHill Cemetery, near the late residence.
     Up to the ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Interment was made in the family lot in The BuckHill Cemetery, near the late residence.
Up to the >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 day of his , Mr. Dietrich's habitual energy, self-reliance and desire to be useful characterized his daily life. He refused to retire in the usual sense of the word, and was carrying a farm program worthy the effort of a man many years his junior.
 
Bertha M. Dillon
 
Source: Monroe County Beacon dated June 17, 1999

Christina J. Dillon nee Cline
Source:The Monroe County Beacon, dated, June 23, 1947
 
Mrs. Christina Dillon, 55, wife of Charles Dillon, of New Matamoras, died Sunday morning, June 15th, at 2:30 o'clock in Marietta Memorial Hospital following her illness. She was admitted to the hospital Saturday noon. Mrs. Dillon was born: January 7, 1892 in Monroe Co. and spent the greater part of her life in the New Matamoras Community. Her parents were Marshall and Amelia Barlow Cline. She was a member of The Jericho Christian Union Church.
 
Surviving are her husband and twelve sons and daughters. They are: Mrs. Wm. Cross, of Woodsfield; Mrs. Wm. Huffman, Mrs. Manuel Eckelberry, Mrs. James W. Cline and Mrs. Denzil Rinard of New Matamoras; Mrs. Ralph Scott, of Alliance; Mrs. Charles Durant and Mrs. Roy Bauer, of Canton; Charles Dillon, Jr., Robert Dillon, Edwin Dillon and William Dillon, of the family home. There are 11 grand children. Brothers and sisters are Stewart Cline, of Burlington Heights; Hershel Cline, of Griffin, Indiana; Roy Cline, of Graysville; Mrs. Alice Howell and Mrs. Olive Yost, of Woodsfield.
 
Funeral services were held Tuesday afternoon at two o'clock at The Jericho
Church. Interment was in the cemetery nearby.
 
E. Matt Dillon
 
Source:The Marietta Times, dated Thursday, October 2, 2003
 
Summerfield: E. Matt Dillon, 76, of 598 Tennis Center Drive, Marietta, died at 4:55 a.m. Wednesday (October 1, 2003) at Marietta Memorial Hospital in Marietta. He was born September 30, 1927, in Morehead, Ky., to George and Rosie Hesson Dillon. He was a retired truck driver and a Protestant by faith.
 
He is survived by his wife, Margaret M. Leasure Dillon, whom he married on October 23, 1982; one stepson, Robert V. Waterman of Marietta; one sister, Edith Trent of Morehead, Ky.; six stepgrandchildren; and four stepgreat-grandchildren.
 
He was preceded in by his parents; one brother, Albert Dillon; and one sister, Bertha Dulin.
 
Services are at 11 a.m. Saturday at Watters Funeral Home in Woodsfield. Burial will follow in Mount Tabor Cemetery near Summerfield. Friends will be received from 2 to 4 and 7 to 9 p.m. Friday at the funeral home.

Dougherty, Henry
Died: April 25, 1921
Woodsfield
Source:The Spirit of Democracy, Woodsfield, Ohio, Thursday, April 28, 1921
  Sergeant Henry Dougherty of Woodsfield, one of Monroe Countys most highly respected Civil war ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Sergeant Henry Dougherty of Woodsfield, one of Monroe County s most highly respected Civil war >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 veterans, died at his home in Woodsfield Monday morning, April 25, 1921, at 8:20 after a short illness from heart trouble, aged 78 years, 5 months and 7 days of age.
  Sergeant ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Sergeant >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Dougherty was not only a citizen of many good qualities, ever sanctioning the right and doing all in his power for the betterment of mankind and those about, but was a soldier of the Civil war and a savior of American integrity with a was record of more than three years which for meritorious work and achievement was surpassed by few if any.
  He enlisted ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> He enlisted >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 under the Stars and stripes, October 5, 1861, and was mustered in as a private to serve three years in Company K, 62nd Ohio Volunteer Infantry under Captain William Dougherty, Henry R. West, and John D. Kennedy. His regiment left for Cumberland, Maryland on January 17, 1862, and was attached to 2nd Brig. Landers Division, Army of the Potomac in March 1862. With his company he advanced in March 1862, to Winchester, Virginia and from that time on until honorably discharged on October 26, 1864, participated in many of the hardest fought battles of the great was, with a very short hospital record.
  On December ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> On December >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 12, 1861, he was promoted from private Corporal and on September 10, 1862, he was promoted to Sergeant for gallant and meritorious service on the fields of battle.

T. Ruff of this place and Mary and Margaret Dougherty of the home.

F. Raymond Drake
F. Raymond Drake, 76, formerly of Barnesville, died Wednesday (April 12, 1989) at Phoneix. Ariz. He was born in Woodsfield, a son of the late William Garfield Drake and Jenny Bird Drake. He was a Methodist.
Surviving are his wife, Ethel Drake; two sons, Ray of Sierra Vista, Ariz., and Larry of Oxford, AL; three daughters, Dories Merritt, Bonnie Drake and Alice Ballabin, all of Phoenix; five brothers; Bill of Brecksville, WV, George and Charles, both of Barnesville, Thurman and Carl of Bardington, FL; six sisters, Myrtle Hudson of Barnesville, Lillian Huntsman of Columbus, Florence Little of West Lafayette, Edna Parker of Leesburg, FL, Betty Eikleberry of Streetsboro, and Kathryn Eikleberry of Ravenna; 16 grandchildren; 33 great-grandchildren; and a great-great-grandchild.
 
Friends will be received at the Kelly-Kemp Funeral Home, Bethesda, 2 to 4 and 7 to 9 pm Monday, where services will be held at 11 am Tuesday with brother James Gallagher officiating. Burial will be in Ebenezer Cemetery, Bethesda.

LEWISVILLE, Ohio - James Dale Drum, 59, of Lewisville died Friday (January 9, 2004) at Woodsfield. He was born July 1, 1944, in Woodsfield to Raymond E. and Annie Laurie Yockey Drum. He was a retired coal miner from North American No. 4 mine in Clarington, Ohio, and was an avid farmer.
 
He is survived by his wife of 39 years, Connie L. Davis Drum of Lewisville; one daughter, Teri Majors and her husband, Todd, of Woodsfield; three sons, Mickey Drum and his wife, Beth, and Matt Drum and his partner, Robin, all of Lewisville, and Kevin Drum and his wife, Julie, of Woodsfield; one brother, Charles Drum and his wife, Lana, of Maryville, Tenn.; three sisters, Louise Riether and her husband, Charlie, of Lewisville, Mary Wiggins and her husband, Delvin, of Woodsfield and Alice Swindell of Commercial Point, Ohio; five granddaughters, Ariel, Jamie, Hanna, Nikki and Sierrea; six grandsons, Kyle, Cody, Devin, Jordan, Jesse and Vinnie; and several nieces and nephews.
 
He was preceded in by his parents; his mother-in-law and father-in-law, Drexel and Myrtle Rose Davis; and one granddaughter, Deanna.
 
Services are at 2 p.m. today at Bauer-Turner Funeral Home, 100 S. Paul St., Woodsfield. Burial will be at the convenience of the family. Memorial contributions may be made to Warm The Children, in care of Monroe County Beacon, 103 East Court St., Woodsfield, Ohio 43793.

  Ralph E. Drum, ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'>
Ralph E. Drum, >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 son of Mr. and Mrs. Thomas E. Drum, Main Street, Woodsfield, Ohio, recently was presented the Oak Leaf Cluster to his Air Medal "for sustained operational flights on combat operations of a hazardous nature" and was promoted to first lieutenant.
  The decoration ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> The decoration >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 took place at the advanced Southwest Pacific base of the 13th AAF, the "jungle air force", from which the veteran "Fightin'13th" daily hammers Japanese oil reserves in the Dutch East Indies and Borneo and supports the American liberation forces on Luzon by leaving enemy airdromes in that area unserviceable.
  Lietenant Drum ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Lietenant Drum >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 ,24, who entered the AAF in November ,1941, became an aviation cadet. He trained at a AAF Radio School, Scott Field, Illinois, and at Craig Army Air Field, Selma, Ala., was commissioned and aWarded his pilot's wings April 29, 1943. Lietenant Drum arrived overseas in November that year, and has participated in the Northern Solomons, Bismark Archipelago and New Guinea campaigns for which he is authorized symbolizing battle Stars on his Asiatic-Pacific ribbon. Lieutenant Drum previously was aWarded the Air Medal and Oak Leaf Cluster in addition to the one recently received.
  He is a 1938 ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> He is a 1938 >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 graduate of Woodsfield High School, later attended Miami University, Oxford and Muskingham College, New Concord.   Lt. Drum ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Lt. Drum >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 arrived Tuesday morning for a 21-day furlough at his home, after which he will report for a furthur rest of fifteen days at a reassignment center before reporting somewhere for duty.

January 5, 1915
 
Mildred Luella Dye
 
NEW MATAMORAS - Mildred Luella Dye, 85, of 811 Park Ave. died at 10:30 p.m. Wednesday (Dec. 15, 2004) at Marietta Memorial Hospital.
 
She was born April 3, 1919, in Brownsville (Monroe County), Ohio, to Charles Alfred and Lucinda Coss Placer. She was a member of the Newport Church of Christ. She graduated from Matamoras High School and Canton Beauty School and was a beautician for 35 years.
She was preceded in death by her husband, Theodore S. Dye, in 1981; two brothers, Charles William Placer and John Robert Placer; and three sisters, Helen Burkhammer, Thelma Schmidt and Stella Langsdorf.
 
She is survived by one nephew, Gary Burkhammer; six nieces, Betty Christy, Mary Louise Stewart, Doris Cline, Marion Williamson, Margaret Hartshorn and Frances Hixon; and her neighbors and caregivers, Mike, Teresa, Sara and Shana Swan.
 
Services are at 1 p.m. Sunday at Hadley Funeral Home in New Matamoras with Chris Mullins officiating. Entombment is in East Lawn Memorial Park Cemetery. The family will receive friends from 2 to 4 and 6 to 8 p.m. Saturday at the funeral home.
Source: Marietta Times, Friday, december 17, 2004

George Egger
Fatal Accident
Spirit of Democracy   April 2, 1930
     George Egger, aged 77, of near Lewisville, was instantly killed and his son  Albert Egger slightly injured when their car ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'>Spirit of Democracy April 2, 1930
George Egger, aged 77, of near Lewisville, was instantly killed and his son Albert Egger slightly injured when their car >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 left the roadway just beyond Malaga, Wednesday evening of last week about 5:00 o'clock. Just about 100 feet over the Bemont-Monroe County line near the D.L. Hagan farm, the road makes a curve, and apparently Albert, who was driving, was blinded by the blizzard and failed to negotiate the curve. Holding to a straight course one or two seconds to long would take a car from the roadway, and it overturned in the cornfield below the road. The younger Egger was stunned temporarily but his father was killed out-right. His skull was crushed and vertebrae of his neck dislocated either of which would have caused his death.
     The ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> The >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 accident was discovered by G. J. Whalen, who is working on the Barnesville Hospital Campaign. Mr. Whalen was returning from Woodsfield when he noticed the overturned car, an old Maxwell touring.
     He stopped ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> He stopped >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 and went to the scene of the accident, finding Albert Egger bent over still dazed from the expierence and his father lying nearby. He examined the latter and found that he was dead.

January 2, 1923
 
Miltonsburg
 
Egger, John H.
JOHN H. EGGER
 
John H. Egger, of Wheeling, the head of the well-known house of
Egger, Warrick & Co., dry goods, was born in Monroe County, Ohio,
April 25, 1853. There he was reared and attended the common schools
of the County until he was seventeen years of age, when he left the
farm and became a clerk in a dry goods store in his native County.
Going west in 1874 he remained there two years, which he spent in the
dry goods business, and returning to his native County he again
entered the dry goods house in which he continued until 1879, when he
came to Wheeling, where he took a position as clerk in the
establishment of Henry Jacobs & Co. He remained with that house
eight years, then in 1887, after serving seventeen years, at the age
of thirty-four he formed the firm of Egger, Warrick & Co., the
members of the firm being S. B. Warrick and R. B. Roberts. The firm
is composed of young men, all of whom have succeeded through their
own enterprise and devotion to business. Messrs. Egger and Warrick
had been clerks all their life, and Mr. Roberts had been connected
with the nail works, and the capital they invested was the result of
their savings from salaries. Beginning business with a full stock,
they have since increased it over 100 per cent, and though a young
firm, have already taken rank among the leading dry goods men of the
city. Success has met their efforts half way, and their enterprise
is allowing no opportunity for advancement to go on unimproved
assures still greater success in the future. Mr. Egger being the
oldest son and third child of a family of thirteen children, all of
whom are living. Mrs. Egger is the oldest daughter and third child
of a family of thirteen children, a coincidence rarely to be met
with. Of Mrs. Egger's brothers and sisters, eleven are living at
this time.

Egger, Matilda
                  ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Source--News Clipping
Published--1953
Egger, Mrs. Matilda was born in 1863, September 26 in Summit Township, Monroe County on the farm known as Geldmacher farm, a daughter of Frederick and Catherine Rose Geldmacher. She passed away at the home of her niece, Mrs. L.W. Peters on Woodsfield, Route 3, February 15, 1953 at the age of 88 years, four months and 22 days. She was the last member of a family of six children.
                  ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 She was baptized and confirmed in the Evangelical faith in Saint John Evangelical Church near Lewisville.
                  ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 She was married to J.F. Egger, July 29, 1890. He was a school teacher for 20 years and then entered the hardware business. They built a home in Lewisville and lived there for 37 years. Mr. Egger died in 1936 after 46 years of married life.
                  ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 All her life Mrs. Egger was active in church work as was her husband and both recognized the temperance work as a part of Christian service.Mrs. Egger soon became a leader in the Women's Christian Temperance Union and served as County President of Monroe County for 25 years. Their home was always open to the WCTU and church workers and their influence was far reaching. In the church she was organist at Saint John's for over 50 years and taught the men's class for over 25 years. She was a charter member of the Women's Guild, The Sunshine Girls, a group of young women was organized in Mrs. Egger's home by her sister, Miss Clara Geldmacher and met there regularly for five years under Miss Clara's leadership and for 15 years under Mrs. Egger's care, till her husbands death. They were a source of great joy as the name suggests.
                  ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Mrs. Egger traveled extensively, having visited many parts of the United States and resided in Florida for more than a year. She had a large circle of friends in many places. She was a generous contributor to worthy causes realizing that only what we give away can we take with us into Eternity.

Etta Lenoar Eldridge nee McNew
Source:The Marietta Times, dated, Wednesday, June 9, 2004
 
GRAYSVILLE - Etta Lenoar Eldridge, 76, of 39389 Straightfork Road died at 1 a.m. Tuesday (June 8, 2004) at her home. She was born January 24, 1928, in Tazewell, Tenn., to Wesley and Myrtle McCreary McNew. She was a homemaker and a member of Straightfork Chapel.
 
She is survived by her husband, Richard HoWard Eldridge, whom she married on December 12, 1947, in Georgia; three sons, H. Ray Eldridge and his wife, Wanda, of Graysville, Bruce W. Eldridge and his wife, Lynn, of Stow and Bobby Joe Eldridge of Akron; one daughter, Faye McBride and her husband, Charles, of Akron; eight grandchildren; 10 great-grandchildren; two brothers, Paul McNew and his wife, Mary, of Crossville, Tenn., and Willie McNew and his wife, Erica, of Corpus Cove, Texas; and two sisters, Ruby Lawson of Jacsboro, Tenn., and Jewel Cox and her husband, J.C., of Cairo, Ga.
She was preceded in by her parents.
 
Mrs. Eldridge was cremated and memorial services will be held at noon on Saturday at her home at 39389 Straightfork Road for family and friends. Burial is in Akron.
 
Memorial contributions may be made to Straightfork Chapel Church, 39393 Straightfork Road, Graysville, Ohio 45734.
Hadley Funeral Homes, New Matamoras Chapel, is in charge of arrangements.

Elliott-Kuzma
 
Amy Michelle Kuzma and Donald William Elliott were united in marriage Sept. 25 at 3:30 p.m. at Powhatan Presbyterian Church, Powhatan Point, with the Rev. Gregory Stone officiating at the double ring ceremony. The bride was given in marriage by her father. Parents of the bride are Mr. and Mrs. Michael Kuzma of Powhatan Point. Parent of the groom is Rosemary Elliott of Wheeling. Janette Kuzma was maid of honor and Jim Machine served as best man. Other attendants were Jodi Alig, matron of honor and Paul Alig. Delanie Tomlinson was flower girl and Zane and Jacob Thornburg were ring bearers. Chelsea Coleman was guest book and bubble attendant. Margi Francis and Lisa Francis were vocalists. A reception was held at the Moundsville Eagles, Moundsville. The bride is a 1991 graduate of River High School and Swiss Hills Vocational School. She has attended Belmont Technical College. Her husband is a 1992 graduate of Wheeling Park High School. Following a wedding trip to Cancun, Mexico, the couple will reside in Wheeling.

Vernon L. 'Homie' Elliott
 
Woodsfield - Vernon L. "Homie" Elliott, 81, of Woodsfield died Monday (December 8, 2003) at Marietta Memorial Hospital.
 
He was born February 19, 1922, in Monroe County to Raymond W. "Bud" and Sarah Nalley Elliott. He was a retired cartage hauler, and owner of Elliott's Concessions.
 
He is survived by his wife, Evelyn Lucille Denbow Elliott; three sons, Roger Elliott and his wife, Toni, Dale Elliott and his wife, Dorothy, and Robert Elliott, all of Woodsfield; one stepson, Gary Denbow and his wife, Kathy, of Brownsville; two daughters, Bonnie Selvy and her husband, Jim, and Lisa O'Neal and her husband, Dennis, all of Woodsfield; seven grandchildren; three stepgrandchildren; four great-grandchildren; and five stepgreat-grandchildren.
 
He was preceded in by one daughter, Susan Louise Elliott; one son, Terry Elliott; one brother, Homer Elliott; and his parents.
 
Services are at 1 p.m. Thursday at Bauer-Turner Funeral Home in Woodsfield with Pastor Paul Ferguson officiating. Burial is in Oaklawn Cemetery in Woodsfield. Friends will be received from 2 to 4 and 7 to 9 p.m. Wednesday at the funeral home.

July 2, 1933
Ensign, Harold William and Irma Jean Highman
Harold William Ensign - Irma Jean Highman  marriage
======= mso-fareast-language:JA'>Harold William Ensign - Irma Jean Highman marriage >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711
 
Source:  The ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'>Source: The >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Monroe County Beacon, dated, Thursday, Aug. 24, 1950
 
In a double ring  ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'>In a double ring >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 ceremony performed on Saturday afternoon, June seventeenth, at one o'clock, Miss Irma Jean Highman, daughter of Mr. and Mrs. Allen Highman, of Litchfield, Ohio, became the bride of Mr. Harold William Ensign, son of Mr. and Mrs. Clyde Ensign, of Spencer, Ohio, in a lovely lawn wedding at the home of the bride, with Rev. Walter T. Hinzmann officiating.
 
Preceding the ceremony, Miss Wilma Stocker sang "Because" and "I Love You Truly." She was accompanied by Miss Glenna Ayrock.
 
Given in marriage by her father, the bride was attired in a princess style gown of white slipper satin. The high, round neckline yolk was of Chantilly lace with a bertha collar effect. Slipper satin, like that of the collar, formed a Juliet cap to which her fingertip veil of Chantilly lace was attached. She carried a bouquet of white Shasta daisies and mock orange blossoms with a white carnation corsage in the center. She carried out the tradition of "something old, something new, something borrowed and something blue."
 
Miss Betty Foraker, cousin of the bride, was maid of honor. Her short sleeved gown was of yellow marquisette and featured the bertha collar. Bridesmaids were Miss Jo Ann Highman, sister of the bride, and Miss Ruth Curtiss, cousin of the bride. They wore short sleeved gowns of blue satin with overskirts of blue net. They carried blue and yellow Shasta daisies.
 
Mr. Charles Ensign served his brother as best man. Both he and the groom were dressed in light blue suits and wore a white carnation in their lapel.
 
The bride's mother wore a gray bemberg dress with blue accessories and a pink carnation corsage. The mother of the groom wore a powder blue dress with white accessories and a yellow carnation corsage.
 
Immediately following the ceremony a reception was held at the home of the bride, with one hundred guests attending.
 
After the reception the newlyweds left on a short wedding trip. For traveling the bride chose a blue nylon dress with blue accessories and a white carnation corsage.
 
The newlyweds are now residing in Litchfield.

Daniel S. Feasel
 
Source:The Marietta Times, dated Thursday, November 27, 2003
 
Woodsfield - Daniel S. Feasel, 76, of 135 Andover Road died at 5:30 p.m. Tuesday (November 25, 2003) at Wetzel County Hospital in New Martinsville, W.Va. He was born September 16, 1927, in Sistersville, W.Va., to Curtis and Louis Riggs Feasel. He was a U.S. Navy veteran of World War II and the Korean conflict, and was a retired Air Force master sergeant serving during the Vietnam era. He was a member of Veterans of Foreign Wars Post 5303 at Woodsfield, Loyal Order of Moose Lodge at Woodsfield and Fraternal Order of Eagles at Woodsfield. He was also currently serving as a board member on the Monroe County Veterans Service Commission.
 
He is survived by his wife, Leah Swartzlander Feasel, whom he married June 2, 1950; two daughters, Terry Stempfer and her husband, Randy, of Winston-Salem, N.C., and JoEllen Seidler and her husband, Jeff, of Woodsfield; and three grandchildren, Jaren Stempfer, Jason Seidler and Jordan Seidler.
 
He was preceded in by his parents; one brother, Allen Feasel; and one nephew, Mike Swartzlander.
 
Services are at 1 p.m. Saturday at Watters Funeral Home in Woodsfield with Sam Bartrug and Keith Jones officiating. Burial is in Oaklawn Cemetery in Woodsfield with full military graveside services conducted by the Belmont Veterans Council.
 
Friends will be received from 2 to 4 and 7 to 9 p.m. Friday at the funeral home.
 
Fedorachak, Catherine Foreaker

The Spirit of Democracy, Woodsfield, Ohio

October 1, 1982

 

     6th Installment  Another reason for this second tour was to obtain more records on our German and Swiss Families.  These records are becoming more and more difficult to obtain, and even the Mormon Dennis Kastens had gone to great lengths to obtain Catholic records from Dahn to fill in gaps in our families, and after several trips had prevailed on the Catholic priest there to allow him to photo-copy records.  He was also able to trace back five generations on my Monroe Co. Burkhart family to Hausenstein and the furthest is a Valentine Burkhart, b. ca. 1642 at Wernersberg.  Hausenstein and Wernersberg were also ======= style='mso-spacerun:yes'> 6th Installment Another reason for this second tour was to obtain more records on our German and Swiss Families. These records are becoming more and more difficult to obtain, and even the Mormon Dennis Kastens had gone to great lengths to obtain Catholic records from Dahn to fill in gaps in our families, and after several trips had prevailed on the Catholic priest there to allow him to photo-copy records. He was also able to trace back five generations on my Monroe Co. Burkhart family to Hausenstein and the furthest is a Valentine Burkhart, b. ca. 1642 at Wernersberg. Hausenstein and Wernersberg were also >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 included on our tour of German villages, so that I could see the home of these ancestors. I was mildly disappointed with the Catholic Church at Wernerberg, as it is totally modern, and I had difficulty in associating all that modernity with an ancestor born in 1642. I also pick up a new name from a female ancestor here who was the daughter of Hans Ludwig Naab of Dahn and who died in Hauenstein. Gertrude Naab was the dau-in-law of Valentine Burkhart.  It is hoped that the records obtained at Dahn ======= style='mso-spacerun:yes'> It is hoped that the records obtained at Dahn >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 from this Catholic church will also contain these other villages in this same area.

     One of the pre-arrangements for Gstaad was an appointment with Herr Fritz Kirchner and his wife. Dennis and I had met him on the last tour.  He is gaining quite a reputation as being the authority on Saanen genealogy (Switzerland).  He had arranged for Dennis to photo-copy more of these early church books on this visit, and Dennis was filled with great exhilaration at this prospect.  On our way into Switzerland, we made a two-hour stop at Berne for him to obtain a Bebilligung or Permission to search old records in Gsteig, Lenk, and Saanen.  This cost him 20 Swiss francs (The exchange was about two Swiss francs for one American Dollar.)  and it was for one year, and is renewable. Without that he would not have been able to do any research.  While Dennis was so engaged, the rest of us ======= style='mso-spacerun:yes'> One of the pre-arrangements for Gstaad was an appointment with Herr Fritz Kirchner and his wife.      Our itinerary took us through the French-speaking part of Switzerland on our way to Gstaad.      Gstaad is an excellent place for shopping, with all sorts of shops, although for the most part the items were expensive.  I purchased a wool sweater, as the mornings were mostly chilly, although by the mid-morning, the temperature was quite pleasant.  We again ======= style='mso-spacerun:yes'> Gstaad is an excellent place for shopping, with all sorts of shops, although for the most part the items were expensive. Edelweiss is the national flower, and it is an endangered species, so there are laws against picking any of that. We counted about 10 varieties which we new, but there were many more which were not familiar to us.  From the top of the chair lift there were two alternatives, the shorter trail led back to Gtaad, while the longer fork went down into Saanen some kilometers away.      As in Germany, we were given ample breakfasts, more than enough to save something for lunch.  However, Switzerland, a land of meadows and mountains, is also the home of famous cheeses and chocolate, so we always had a choice of much more than we could eat.  Also in Switzerland, it is no bother to keep supplied with fruit. Feiock, Charles E., III
Source--Times Leader  ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'>Source--Times Leader >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Martins Ferry, Ohio
Published--October 19, 2004
            Charles ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Charles >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 E. Feiock III, 83, of 1445 School Avenue North East, North Canton, Ohio (formerly of Lewisville, Ohio) died at 6:45 a.m., Monday, October 18, 2004 at the Aultman Hospital, Canton, Ohio. He was born at Lewisville, Ohio, April 24, 1921, a son of the late Charles Everett and Lola Eddy Feiock. He was a 1939 graduate of Lewisville High School, Lewisville, Ohio. He worked in Parma, Ohio until he was 21 years old and then he enlisted in the United States Navy Air Corps in May of 1942 and getting called up in October 1942. During this time, he went through the Civilian Pilot Training School at New Philadelphia, Ohio. Chuck earned his Navy pilot wings and Ensign rating at Pensacola, Florida and spent the next 22 years serving the Navy, retiring as a Lieutenant Commander after serving during World War II, Korean War and the Viet Nam War. While in the Navy he attended Ohio State University and earned a bachelor of science degree in Meterology from the Naval Post Graduate School in Monterey, California. He was a graduate of the United States. Navy Test Pilot School at Patuxent River, Maryland. He saw duty aboard aircraft carriers in the Mediterranean, was the first Navy pilot to fly the R3Y Trade Wind Plane, served two years in the Philippines and flew about 20 flights to the South Pole while in America. He met Shirley Hallbrerg while he was stationed at Traverse City, Michigan. They married on July 4, 1946 at his parents home in Lewisville, Ohio. After retiring from the Navy, Chuck was the manager for seven years of the Miller Airport in North Benton, Ohio. He then worked in Real Estate. He ended his active working years as a savings counselor for First Federal Savings and Loan of Canton, Ohio. He was a Protestant by faith, a member of the Alliance Elks Club, Alliance, Ohio, Uniontown Rotary Club, Uniontown, Ohio and the Board of Realtors. He was also an avid golfer. He was preceded in death by his parents and wife, Shirley Hallberg Feiock on August 18, 1994. Surviving are his companion, Alice Long of North Canton, Ohio; cousins: Dan and Janet Stoffel of Lewisville, Ohio and Neil and Barbara DeWitt of Canal Winchester, Ohio.Friends will be received Thursday at 11 a.m., until time of services at 1 p.m., with Reverend Karen Benford officiating at the Watters Funeral Home, 37501 State Route 78 West, Woodsfield, Ohio. Burial will follow in the Friendship Cemetery with full military graveside services by the Belmont Veterans Council.
 
Feiock, Ed

Feiock, John W. Feiock
Dies at Hebron
Published  January 11, 1945
     Many ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'>Published January 11, 1945
Many >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 friends in Monroe County regretted last week to learn of the death of John. W. Feiock, 78, at the home of his daughter, Mrs. Marion Robinson at Hebron. He had been in failing health the past year and confined to his bed for several weeks prior to his death, which occurred Thursday evening, January 4.
     Mr. Feiock ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Mr. Feiock >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 was born September 30, 1866 in Lewisville, and was a son of George and Katherine (Butt) Feiock. He grew to manhood in that community and for a number of years operated a hotel in Lewisville during the oil boom period and before the day of automobile travel. His pleasing personality and congeniality made many friends and he was elected sheriff of Monroe County serving from 1910 to 1914. He also served as deputy fire Marshall of Monroe, Belmont and Washington counties by appointment when James M. Cox was governor.
     Twenty-two ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Twenty-two >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 years ago he moved to Hebron. He was always an ardent Democrat, but in 1924 he was elected Mayor of Hebron, serving two terms and was again elected in 1943. In the interim he served as a justice of the peace.
     Kindness, ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Kindness, >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 justice and fairness in his relations with people were outstanding characteristics of his personality, always. He was a member of St. Peter's Evangelical & Reformed Church in Lewisville and also of Hebron Lodge F. & A.M.
     Besides his ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Besides his >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 widow, Louisa (Friday) Feiock, he is survived by one daughter, Eunice, Mrs. Marion Robinson; a grandson, Paul Robinson, in The U.S. Navy. and one brother Charles E. Feiock, of Lewisville.

Mrs. Fred Feldner
Mrs. Fred Feldner Dies At Home Here
June 1, 1944
 
    Thursday afternoon of last week, relatives and friends were shocked by the sudden death of  Mrs. Fred Feldner which occured at her home on Eastern Avenue at 3 o'clock.
    Within the ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'>
Thursday afternoon of last week, relatives and friends were shocked by the sudden death of Mrs. Fred Feldner which occured at her home on Eastern Avenue at 3 o'clock.
Within the >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 past two months she had suffered two attacks of pneumonia, from which she had apparently recovered, and on Wednesday had planned to spend the next day with her sister-in-law, Mrs. George Reich as her guest.
    Wednesday night she suffered a third  and more severe attack of pneumonia which ran a rapidly fatal course.
    Mrs. Feldner was born at Hannibal, Ohio, February 14, 1872, a daughter of Jacob and Dora Nething.  She grew to womanhood there and on September 5, 1893, was united in marriage with Fred Feldner at Beaver Falls, Penna. They began housekeeping in Woodsfield and maintained their home here until they both passed to their "home not made with hands, eternal in the heavens."  Her husband preceded her in death, September 25, 1937.
    Mr. and Mrs. Feldner reared two fine sons, Walter and Edward, of Pittsburg. She is also survived by one brother,  William Nething of Ravenna, Ohio and one grandson,  ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Wednesday night she suffered a third and more severe attack of pneumonia which ran a rapidly fatal course.

 Provided by Lena Kahrig Pettit, typed by Betty Lendon Matson
  County ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Provided by Lena Kahrig Pettit, typed by Betty Lendon Matson
County >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Commissioner, Henry H. Fliehman, died suddenly at his home here Tuesday evening (4/19/32), about 11:00 o'clock. While he had been suffering for several months from heart ailments, he was going about his work as usual and is said to have spent Tuesday on his farm plowing.
  A short time ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> A short time >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 before retiring, he complained slightly of some bodily discomfort which he probably ascribed to fatigue and as he was on his way to his bedroom he collapsed and death was almost instantaneous. A physician was summoned but medical aid was unavailing.
  Mr. Fliehman ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Mr. Fliehman >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 was about 69 years of age and is survived by his widow and four children. He came to Woodsfield from Bethel Township several years ago and was well known throughout the County.
  Mr. Fliehman ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Mr. Fliehman >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 was completing his first term of four years as County commissioner and declined to enter the campaign for renomination on account of his health.
  Funeral ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> Funeral >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 services will be held at St. Paul's Evangelical Church on South Main St., Woodsfield, Friday afternoon at 2 o'clock in charge of Rev. William J. Jones, pastor of The Woodsfield M.E. Church, assisted by Rev. Henry Fox, pastor of St. Paul's. Mr. Fliehman was confirmed in The Evangelical faith when a youth but was liberal in his denominational opinions and belief. He was a member of The Men's Bible Class of The Woodsfield M.E. Church. Interment was in Oaklawn Cemetery.

John Adam Fliehmann
Source:Newspaper clipping, Monroe County, Ohio
 John Adam ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> John Adam >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Fliehmann died early on Friday morning, April 23, 1886, in Center township. He was born in the Palatines, Germany in 1826, immigrated in 1842, and made his home in Monroe County Ohio. He married Lena, daughter of Lawrence Neuhart, Esq., with whom he had 13 children, 10 boys and three girls; one of the latter died in early youth, five of whom live in this County and seven have their home in Motgomery Co, Missouri. His wife died July 30, 1883. He served through the Mexican War. When the War of the Rebellion broke out in 1861, he entered the Union Army and was made first Lieutenat seventh Regiment, W. Va, Infantry. During the battle of Antetam a Ball grazed his head, which rendered him unfit for further service; he received an honorable discharge and drew a pension. A year ago his health began to fail him, and since the beginning of the present year he suffered from inflammation of the bowels and reached the age of about 60 years. He was buried at Neuhart graveyard, 2 miles East of Woodsfield, by the side of his wife. Rev. Albert J. Witerich conducted the funeral service.
 
Fleming, Robert
Source--Times Leader   ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'>Source--Times Leader >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Martins Ferry, Ohio
Published--February 2, 2005
 
Fleming , Robert Michael , age 52, of Long Ridge Road, Clarington, died Tuesday, February 1, 2005 in Doctors Hospital, Columbus, Ohio. He was born on January 4, 1953 in Wetzel County, West Virginia., the son of Robert A. Fleming and the late Rosetta Schaum Fleming. He was a former employee of Valley National Gas in Wheeling and Auto Zone in New Martinsville. He was a member of Zion United Church of Christ in Sardis, a graduate of River High School, previous member of the Adena Lions Club, and a member of the Zion Grange, Hannibal. In addition to his father, survivors include his wife, Joyce Huffman Fleming; two daughters, Mrs. Steve (Tawyna) Jones and Mrs. Chris (Tara) Green, all of Hilliard, Ohio, grandchildren, Steven, Alyssa and Robbie Jones and an expected baby Green; a sister, Mrs. Marvin (Barbara) Ruckman of Proctor, West Virginia., father-in-law and mother-in-law Jack and Deloris Ann Huffman of Sardis; a sister-in-law, Mary Huffman of Sardis; three nephews, a niece, many other family and friends.A memorial service will be held on Saturday, February 12, 2005 at 2 p.m. at the Hilltop Community Center, Route 536, Hannibal. In lieu of flowers, memorial contributions may be made to the American Diabetes Association, Post Office Box 1115, 1221-A Ohio Ave., Dunbar, West Virginia. 25064. Arrangements entrusted to Grisell Funeral Home, Clarington, Ohio.

Steel coil crushes plant worker
by Rick Stillion
The Daily Jeffersonian
BYESVILLE - An apparent accident at Monogram Metals on Leyshon Drive here claimed the life of a Fairview man Tuesday night when he was crushed by a steel coil.
Bryan Flynn, 30, was pronounced dead at Southeastern Med, where he was transported by United Ambulance following the accident at 9:46 p.m.
An emergency 911 call to the Guernsey County Sheriff's Office reported the accident.
A sheriff's dispatcher alerted United Ambulance and subsequently the Byesville Volunteer Fire Department.
When we arrived at the scene, plant employees had already extricated the victim out from under the steel coil, said Byesville Fire Chief Tad Thompson. At that point, we assisted United with loading the patient and transporting him to the hospital.
According to reports, a steel coil fell from a piece of equipment at the plant and struck Flynn. He was reportedly in cardiac arrest as he was transported to the hospital.
Guernsey County Coroner Dr. Janet Brockwell ruled it was an accidental death due to internal injuries caused by massive, blunt-force trauma to the abdominal and pelvic area.

Blanche A. Foster nee Herlan
TIMES RECORDER, ZANESVILLE, OHIO, 8 Aug 1970
Mrs. Blanche A. Foster [aka, Alma B. "Blanche" (Herlan) Foster], 84, of Drake Nursing Home on Findley avenue, retired housemother of the old Bethesda School of Nursing, died at 5:05 p.m. Friday (August 7) at the nursing home where she had been a patient several years. She was born June 1, 1886, in Summerfield, a daughter of John W. and Sarah Kent Herlan. She spent most of her life in the Zanesville area. Her husband, Delbert G. Foster, died in 1942. Mrs. Foster was Bethesda housemother 17 years before retiring in 1964. She was a member of Grace United Methodist Church.
She leaves a daughter, Mrs. Donald (Fern) Lane of West Pike; a son, John Foster of Jackson; a brother, Elbert Herlan of Parma; seven grandchildren; and six great-grandchildren; and a number of nieces and nephews. A daughter, three brothers and four sisters are deceased. Friends may call at Blue Avenue Chapel of Bolin Funeral Home 2 to 4 and 7 to 9 p.m. Sunday.

Frank, August Frank
September 3, 1854
October 7, 1916
Lewisville
August Herman Frank -- Once more the death angel has visited this vicinity and claimed for its victim a beloved husband and father, August Frank. Although he had been failing in health for the past year or more, nothing seemed more serious until on Wednesday evening when he was stricken ill while at work in the field. Death come the following Saturday morning. All that loving hands and medical skill could was done but death had gained its way. Deceased was born September 3, 1854, and departed this life October 7, 1916, being at the time of his death 62 years, one month and four days old. He was united in marriage to Matilda Keeyser April 6, 1884. To this union ten children were born, three of them dying in infancy. He leaves to mourn his departure a wife, six sons and one daughter and three grandchildren, besides a host of relatives and friends. He will not only be missed by his family but by everyone that knew him. He was a kind and loving father and neighbor, none knew him but to love him. In early manhood he united with the Lutheran church at Lewisville. Funeral services were conducted by Rev. Penell; interment in Barber Ridge cemetery.
 
, 1912
FRANK, Caroline (nee Brubach)
               Caroline FRANK (nee Brubach) the ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Caroline FRANK (nee Brubach) the >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 subject of this sketch, was born in Rumbach, Bavaria Province in Germany, May 4th, 1830, and died near Miltonsburg, Monroe County, Ohio at 2:30 O'clock, Tuesday afternoon, February 27, 1912, being at the time of her 81 years, 9 months and 23 days old.
               She came to this country with her ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> She came to this country with her >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 parents at the age of 10 years and their place of settlement was in Summit township, Monroe County.  Miss Caroline Brubach was confirmed in the old St. Peter's Evangelical church of near Miltonsburg at an early age and endeavored to live according to that faith until claimed by .  On the 23rd day of August 1851, Caroline Brubach and Oscar FRANK were united in marriage and moved south to Lewisville and to this union were born ten children, 3 of whom preceded the mother to the great beyond and also the husband, Oscar FRANK preceded her June 4, 1890.  Those living to mourn the departure of the soul are seven children, 3 boys and four girls, namely: August FRANK of near Lewisville, Charlie F. FRANK of Shadyside, Oscar J. FRANK of Donora, Pa, Mrs. M. J. YOUNG of Summit township, Mrs. George Feiock of Tarantum, Pa., Mrs. E. E. Cronin of near Lewisville, and Miss Henrietta FRANK who has made her home with her mother during her many years of suffering, and has been the comfort of the aged parent until the last hour.  She also leaves to mourn 47 grandchildren, and 18 great-grandchildren, three brothers, Charlie Brubach, Jacob Brubach and Henry Brubach and a host of friends.  "Blessed are they that die in <<<<<<< HEAD the Lord."                                     Mrs. ======= the Lord." Mrs. >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Frank was a woman in the true sense of the word, strictly honest, temperate and industrious, a kind and indulgent mother, and a good neighbor and useful citizen. She was one of those women whose honor and integrity of principle we could all copy after with profit.
               It was known in the surrounding ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> It was known in the surrounding >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 community that  Mrs. Frank was sick for a Long time and suffered untold agony but she never complained. Her sickness was a complication of diseases incident to her advanced age. The family and friends with aid of Dr. C. W. Keysor of Miltonsburg did all that loving hands could do but to no avail. At last the grim reaper came and put his cold and icy hands on one that was so near and dear to us on February 29, 1912.
                With short services at the house ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'>  With short services at the house >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 the remains were followed to Lewisville by a large concourse of relatives and friends and her remains were laid to rest in the cemetery adjoining the church.  The funeral services were conducted by Rev. J. H. Overbeck of Woodsfield.  He took for his text John; 9th chapter, 51st verse, which reads:  "Verily, verily, I say unto you, if a man keep my saying he shall never see ."  The services were conducted in English and the church was crowded with eager listeners.  The sermon was very interesting.
               The family has lost a kind and loving ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> The family has lost a kind and loving >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 mother, the church one of its oldest members and the community one of its best citizens.  Mrs. Frank leaves to mourn three sons, four daughters, three brothers, 47 grandchildren, 18 great-grandchildren and a host of friends but our loss is her eternal gain.  May her soul rest in peace.
                    She ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'>      She >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 had been in poor health for several months but no one thought her end so near until a few days previous to her departure when she was stricken very ill and continued to grow worse until God released her of her suffering and called her to her home of eternal happiness.  Our once happy home is now robed to morning and we realize the sorrow of desolation that rest over us when such a dear one is called away but can only say, God's will be done.  The loss of such a dear one shall never be forgotten by us but our only consolations is that mother is in heaven and we live for our God.  We shall meet her in her eternal home never more to part.
 
     When we think of her cheerful face
          in this world of pain.
     Then of heaven's abiding place
          In the realm of gain,
     Where  no sorrow ever come,
          That to be our home.
      May we meet our dear mother
          Never more to part.

  On Monday ======= mso-fareast-language:JA'> On Monday >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 afternoon, February 18, 1901, at 4 o=clock the angel came in our midst and took from us the beloved wife of Frederick Friday. Mrs. Friday was a sufferer of nasopharyngeal catarrh for years which terminated in consumption which caused her . Mrs. Friday was the daughter of David and Magdalena Ketterer Bintz. She was born July 2, 1862, and married Frederick Friday on January 1, 1890. To this union three children were born, two of whom are still living. Alice preceded her to the better land October 4, 1893. Mrs. Friday was a member of the German Lutheran Church. She had a constant Christian life, gentle, loving and loved by all that knew her. In all her Long suffering she never once complained but bore it all in a Christian spirit, only complaining that she was so much trouble to those who administered to her needs, often expressing the wish to die and be with her Savior. AI am going to Jesus@ was the last words that passed her lips. She leaves to mourn a husband, one son and one daughter, father, two brothers, 3 sisters, and an aged grandmother, besides a host of other relatives and friends. SOURCE: Marietta Times . . Marietta, OH . . Sept 2001 . .
Minnie K. Fulmer, 92, of 109 Heiss St., Marietta, died at 11:30 p.m. Monday (Sept. 17, 2001) at Heartland of Marietta.
She was born Feb. 5, 1909, in Barnesville to Minnie Goodwin. She graduated from Woodsfield High School and Marietta Commercial College. She was a homemaker. She volunteered at Marietta Memorial Hospital. She was active in P.T.A. She was a member of Sixth and Washington Streets Church of Christ and was a Bible school teacher. She enjoyed flowers and sewing.
Due to her mother's death, she was raised by an uncle and aunt, Wilson and Mary Goodwin.
She is survived by two daughters, Barbara Casto of Marietta and Ann Elliott of Lowell; four grandchildren, Stephen Elliott and his wife, Lorrie, and Dr. David Casto and his wife, Kathy, all of Marietta, Debra Taylor and her husband, Bruce, of Marietta, Ga., and Amy Roth and her husband, Chris, of West Chester; and eight great-grandchildren, Jennifer Burns of Little Hocking, Justin and Stevi Elliott and Brian and Maurie Casto, all of Marietta, Renna and Kelsey Taylor of Marietta, Ga., and Daniel Roth of West Chester.
On Aug. 22, 1930, she married Floyd Fulmer. He died Feb. 10, 1985. She was also preceded in death by her mother and one granddaughter, Kathryn Burns.
Services are at 11 a.m. Friday at Hadley Funeral Home, Reno Chapel, with Roger Rush officiating. Burial is in East Lawn Memorial Park. The family will receive friends from 6:30 to 8:30 p.m. Thursday at the funeral home.

Published--September 20, 2004
 
25th: JERRY, CAROL FULTON
 
JACOBSBURG -- Jerry and Carol Fulton of Armstrong-Centerville Road, will celebrate their 25th wedding anniversary. They were united in marriage September 21, 1979 at Elizabeth City, North Carolina, with Harry B. Umpohlt officiating at the ceremony. Fulton is the son of Eileen Fulton of Belmont and the late Charles Fulton. He is employed as an electrical foreman with The W.G. Fairfield Company of Canton. His wife, Carol, is the daughter of Patricia Donley of Holloway and Donald Van Fossen of Flushing. She is manager with Helping Hands Medical Supplies of Moundsville. The couple plans to celebrate their anniversary aboard a Royal Caribbean Cruise Liner, Enchantment of the Seas, touring Georgetown, Grand Cayman and Ocho Rios, Jamaica, as well as vacationing in Fort Lauderdale, Florida.
